# Rule 1 — Architecture

**Never break OpenMeta architecture.** North star: `.cursor/context/project.md`.  
If unclear → stop and ask. Sources: `ARCHITECTURE.md`, `packages/*/SPEC.md`, `docs/adr/`.

## OpenMeta architecture

- WordPress-first content-modeling framework (modular monorepo).
- Packages isolate capabilities; share contracts through `core` (container, providers, events).
- Plugin entry (`openmeta.php`) is thin — boot only, no business logic.
- SPEC-first: implement only what that package’s SPEC allows (Responsibilities / Must not).

```text
WordPress → Plugin Bootstrap → Service Container → Core services
  → Fields / Validation / Security / Database
  → REST · Admin UI · Builder · Developer API
```

## Layering

Keep boundaries sharp. Outer layers **consume** inner layers; they do **not** reimplement them.

| Layer | Owns | Must not own |
| ----- | ---- | ------------ |
| Wordpress glue | Hooks, mount, bridges | Field types, validation engine, schema |
| Admin / Builder / UI | Screens, canvas, chrome | Persistence, public REST server, field engine |
| API | HTTP REST auth + resources | Field-type definitions, admin menus |
| Fields | Field model, render, field storage adapters | WP menus, full GraphQL server |
| Database | Connection, schema, migrations, query | Field UI, REST routes |
| Validation / Security | Rules, caps, nonce, escape | Storage, HTTP routing |
| Core | App, container, kernel, providers, config, events | Any domain package feature |
| Support | Pure helpers | Domain logic |

One package at a time. Coding order: see `.cursor/context/roadmap.md`.

## Package dependency rules

Downstream → upstream only. **Never invert.**

```text
Core ← Support ← Validation ← Security ← Database ← Fields
  ← API / UI ← Admin ← Builder ← Wordpress (glue)
```

- `core` depends on **zero** other OpenMeta packages.
- Do not import Admin from Fields, Database from API, Builder from Wordpress internals, etc.
- Detail table: `.cursor/rules/dependency-rules.mdc`. New edge → update SPEC first.

## SOLID

- **S** — one reason to change per class / package spine component  
- **O** — extend via providers, registries, contracts — not core edits  
- **L** — honor interface contracts; don’t weaken fail-closed security  
- **I** — small contracts over god interfaces  
- **D** — depend on abstractions (container bindings), not foreign concretes  

Also: separation of concerns, simplicity over cleverness, additive public APIs (deprecate don’t delete).

## Dependency Injection (DI)

- Resolve collaborators through the **Core Container** + **ServiceProviders** (register → boot).
- Prefer constructor injection; avoid service-locator sprawl in domain code.
- No hidden `$GLOBALS` domain state; no `new` collaborator graphs that bypass the container in app services.
- WordPress bridges: fail closed when WP APIs missing (`function_exists` / runtime adapters).

## Never break architecture

- ❌ Business logic in `openmeta.php`, templates, or random root scripts  
- ❌ Reimplement Fields / Validation / Security / Database inside Admin, Builder, or API  
- ❌ Skip SPEC / ADR when they exist  
- ❌ Guess when docs conflict — **stop and ask**  
- ❌ Cross-package shortcuts that violate Dependency Rules  

**Done only if** SPEC Must not still holds and `composer ci` can stay green.
